snippet.textDisplay:
Regarding the Trolley dilemma, VSauce actually did a simulation with real world participants (obviously they took great measures to make sure everything was safe and fine) and an overwhelming majority of people didn't switch the switch. In fact, just one person did.
It comes from an inner struggle with not knowing how to react which led to people just doing nothing, and no one can think rationally in that situation. When you don't know what to do, you do nothing at all. Sort of like deer in the headlights.
So no, Kressh. You wouldn't pull the leaver. Everyone thinks they would, but no one does.

snippet.textDisplay:
Others have further expanded the Trolley Problem by having you compare it to the following issue. It's a hypothetical that would never happen, but just go with it. It sounds something like: You're the only doctor in an ER. Six people come in, all needing transplants using different organs to save their lives. The only other person in the hospital is a janitor. You can kill the janitor and use his organs to save six lives.


Essentially, this is the same thing as the trolley. One life on one track that you choose to kill by pulling a switch to save six. Or you kill someone to harvest their organs to save six other people. The outcome is the same: One life for six.


Doesn't really feel the same, does it?

snippet.textDisplay: So, I just want to point out that with the leg argument, prosthetics are getting pretty good. They're not good enough to replace a leg entirely, of course, but how much do we actually do with our legs anyway? Walk, and kick, and do things like walking that are somewhat faster -- basically, locomotion and some elements of fighting. That's it. If all that's needed to save 5 people's lives is to give up some locomotive freedom, I'd say that's an easy trade. And if nothing else, I'd bet in several decades prosthetics will be good enough that they're basically a new flesh-and-bones leg anyway.
snippet.textOriginal: So, I just want to point out that with the leg argument, prosthetics are getting pretty good. They're not good enough to replace a leg entirely, of course, but how much do we actually do with our legs anyway? Walk, and kick, and do things like walking that are somewhat faster -- basically, locomotion and some elements of fighting. That's it. If all that's needed to save 5 people's lives is to give up some locomotive freedom, I'd say that's an easy trade.
